      <div class="post1">
        <h3 style="margin-top:0em;">Course Communication</h3>

<p>
We will use <a href="https://piazza.com/class/jcgi6oe2qya6hv">Piazza</a>
for announcements and student Q&As.
Make sure to sign up and check often!
If you have a question, then almost certainly other students do, too.
</p>
</p>
For individual issues, you can contact the instructor and/or TAs via email.
If you do, please say or enter the string "[PFP]" in the subject line
to help direct your call.
<p>

      </div>
      </div>

      <div class="content_next">
      <div class="post1">
        <h3 style="margin-top:0em;">Grading</h3>

<p>
Grades will be based on programming assignments, written exams, and a
course project according to the following weights:

<ul>
  <li><tt>40%</tt> : Labs (~5-7)</li>
  <li><tt>30%</tt> : Course Project</li>
  <li><tt>30%</tt> : Exams (2)</li>
</ul>
</p>

<h4>Labs</h4>

Programming assignments will be released approximately every week
or two and will be your primary vehicle for digging deeply into the
course material.

<h4>Late Days</h4>

<p>
You may not turn in your work late.</br>
(Late assignments recieve zero credit.)
</p>

<h4>Course Project</h4>

<p>
The course project will be your opportunity to design and implement
something of your choice. You will find more details
<a href="./assignments/project/index.html">here</a>,
but generally the idea is to work
in groups of one or two and build something fun and interesting in Elm
that makes use of web programming and data structures in some way. Set your
aims high, to contribute an interesting project to the Elm community!
</p>
<p>
The project will be split into several milestones, culminating in
demos at the end of the quarter.
</p>

<h4>Exams</h4>

<p>
We will have two in-class written exams, each of which will
cover roughly half of the course material. The exams will be
equally weighted.
</p>

      </div>
      </div>

      <div class="content_next">
      <div class="post1">
        <h3 style="margin-top:0em;">Textbook and Other Resources</h3>

<img height=150px align="left" src="./static/images/Oka.jpg"/ style="padding-right: 20px">

<p>
The required textbook for the course is
Chris Okasaki's
<a
href="http://www.amazon.com/Purely-Functional-Structures-Chris-Okasaki/dp/0521663504">Purely
Functional Data Structures</a>, which is a time-honored classic.
Although we will not cover the book in its entirety this quarter,
it will serve as a trusty reference on your bookshelf going forward...
assuming you still have a physical bookshelf!
</p>
<p>
In addition to the textbook, we will use various other electronic
references that will be linked to in the lecture notes. Because we
will be doing our programming in <a href="http://elm-lang.org/">Elm</a>,
the language documentation &mdash; including the
<a href="https://guide.elm-lang.org/">Elm Guide</a>,
<a href="http://elm-lang.org/docs/syntax">Syntax Reference</a>,
<a href="http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-lang/core/5.1.1/">Core Library Documentation</a>,
and <a href="http://elm-lang.org/examples">Examples</a>
pages &mdash; will become good friends of yours before long.
</p>

